data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Analysis

Your code has **3 patterns** that break on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` in `ProcessLoop` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Prevents rethrow for clean `finally` | Remove entirely — not needed with cooperative cancellation |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully.
        // Unlike Thread.Abort, there is no forced kill — the thread
        // must cooperate by checking the token.
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot interrupt `Thread.Sleep` or `WaitOne` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Abort throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *Removed* | Cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow — no reset needed |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of blindly sleeping |
| — | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` owns timers/callbacks and must be disposed |

### Critical: Update GetNextItem to Accept the Token

The old `GetNextItem()` "may block" — and **cancellation can't interrupt it unless you pass the token**. This is the #1 pitfall:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, no way to cancel
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` does synchronous I/O (e.g., polling a database), replace `Thread.Sleep` waits inside it with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so the sleep is interruptible.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token through the full call chain** | `Cancel()` fires but nothing happens — the thread hangs at the blocking call forever |
| **Expecting cancellation to be immediate** | It only fires at the next `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or token-aware API call. Insert checkpoints between expensive operations in `ProcessItem` |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Let it propagate up to the loop level. Only catch at the top-level orchestration point |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timer and callback registrations |
| **No graceful-stop timeout strategy** | If the thread doesn't exit after `Join(2s)`, you have no fallback. Log a warning — there is no equivalent of force-kill in modern .NET for managed threads |

### If GetNextItem Cannot Be Modified

If the blocking call is third-party code that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort — that's the only true force-stop available in modern .NET.
